ve been revealed and remedial legislation debated, and the Iran-Contra affair has highlighted anew the extent of disagreement over first principles. Exploring the implications of these and earlier foreign policy disputes, Michael Glennon maintains that the objectives of diplomacy cannot be successfully pursued by discarding constitutional interests. Glennon probes in detail the important foreign-policy responsibilities given to Congress by the Constitution and the duty given to the courts of resolving disputes between Congress and the President concerning the power to make foreign policy. He reviews the scope of the prime tools of diplomacy, the war power and the treaty power, and examines the concept of national security. Throughout the work he considers the intricate weave of two legal systems: American constitutional principles and the international law norms that are part of the U.S. domestic legal system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aBerger, Raoul.  aBernstein exception.  aBoland Amendment.  aBricker amendment.  aBumpers amendment.  aCardozo, Benjamin.  aCharles II.  aCongo rescue mission.  aConnally reservation.  aDominican Republic.  aEagleton, Thomas.  aGeneral Accounting Office.  aGrenada.  aGulf of Tonkin Resolution.  aHamilton, Alexander.  aHeritage Foundation.  aHonduras.  aImpoundment Control Act.  aJackson, Robert.  aJapan treaty.  aKorean Airline shoot-down.  aLaos.  aMassachusetts.  aNational Security Act of 1947.  aNiagara Reservation.  aOxford Union.  aPlatt amendment.  aRestatement of Agency.  aSaigon.  aSandalow, Terry.  aStewart, Potter.  aactio popularis.  aadverse possession.  aassassination.  achecks and balances.  aconfirmation power.  acovert operations.